For example, suppose we knew the average height of adult women in the United States is 64 inches, with a variance of 9 inches. As we will see below, the standard deviation is the square root of the variance, so the standard deviation for the height of adult women is \(\sqrt{9} = 3\).

To illustrate the calculations below, we will randomly sample from the above described population, with the assumption that the height of women is normally distributed, which is a reasonable assumption. To help build our intuitions about these conceptual formulas, we will keep the sample small for now.

Lets randomly sample 10 women from our population. To do this in R we need three values the sample size (n), the mean, and the standard deviation (sd). Then we can use the rnorm() function to create a vector of heights as:

set.seed(1234)
height_women <- rnorm(n = 10, mean = 64, sd = 3)

I used set.seed(1234) to make this example reproducible. See ?set.seed for more information.

If, for the vector \(X\) we define another vector of deviation scores, \(x\), as the difference between each value in \(X\) and the mean of \(X\), \(\bar{X}\) as \(x = X - \bar{X}\), then:

\[ s_x^2 = \frac{\Sigma{(X - \bar{X})^2}}{N - 1} = \frac{x^2}{N- 1} \tag{2.1} \] Lets use R to calculate the variance of our height_women variable

X <- height_women
N <- length(X)

First, I created a variable X which is just a copy of height_women, then I created a scalar N which is the number of women in our sample, which is 10.

We will use the deviation score to calculate the variance, so I create it here:

# Calculate deviation scores.
x <- X - mean(X)

Finally, we calculate the variance and assign it to the symbol sx2

# Calculate variance using deviation scores with equation (2.1)
sx2 <- sum(x^2)/(N - 1)

# Print variance
sx2
[1] 8.924335

The sample variance 8.9 is very close to the population variance of womens height which we said was 9. We can think of the variance as the average squared deviation of the sample scores from their mean.

We did these hand calculations to demonstrate the concepts underlying the variance. We can calculate it much easier with the var() function:

var(X)
[1] 8.924335

The standard deviation is the square root of the variance, so we can calculate it is various ways as follows.

sx <- sqrt((sum(x^2))/(N-1)) # by 'hand'
sx
[1] 2.987363
sd(X) # built-in R function
[1] 2.987363

Covariance

The formula for covariance is similar to that of the variance.

\[ s_{xy} = \frac{\Sigma{(X - \bar{X})(Y - \bar{Y})}}{N - 1} = \frac{\Sigma{xy}}{N - 1} \tag{2.3} \]
